{{NHL award
|trophy_name = Clarence S. Campbell Bowl
|Image = Hhof campbell.jpg
|Established= [[1967-68 NHL season]]
|Holder = [[Anaheim Ducks]]
|Awarded = Western Conference champions of the [[National Hockey League]]
}}
The '''Clarence S. Campbell Bowl''', or the '''Campbell Trophy''', is a [[National Hockey League]] trophy awarded to the [[Western Conference (NHL)|Western Conference]] playoff champions.<ref name="NHL">{{cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/trophies/campbell.html|title=Clarence S. Campbell Bowl|publisher=[[NHL]]|accessdate=2007-08-31}}</ref> It is named after [[Clarence S. Campbell]], the former President of the NHL from [[1946-47 NHL season|1946-47]] to [[1976-77 NHL season|1976-77]]. The trophy itself is constructed of sterling silver, crafted in [[1878]].<ref name="NHL" /> The [[Anaheim Ducks]] are the current holders of the trophy after winning the [[2007 Stanley Cup Playoffs|2007 Western Conference playoffs]].

== History ==
The Clarence S. Campbell Bowl was donated by the NHL's clubs in recognition of the contributions and services of its namesake, the League President at the start of the [[History_of_the_National_Hockey_League#Expansion:_1967-2000|Modern Era expansion]]. Throughout its history it has been a parallel to the [[Prince of Wales Trophy]], using the same criteria in the opposite competitive grouping. From its inception in the [[1967-68 NHL season|1967-68]] season through to [[1973-74 NHL season|1973-74]] it was awarded to the first-place finisher in the [[NHL Western Division|West Division]] during the regular season.<ref name="NHL" /> With NHL realignment in [[1974-75 NHL season|1974-75]], it was given to the team with the best regular-season record in the [[Western Conference (NHL)|Campbell Conference]] (the successor to the West Division) through the [[1980-81 NHL season|1980-81]] season.<ref name="NHL" /> Beginning with the [[1981-82 NHL season|1981-82]] season, it switched to the Campbell Conference ''playoff'' champions, and since the [[1993-94 NHL season|1993-94]] season, when the Campbell Conference became the Western Conference, has gone to the Western Conference playoff champions.<ref name="NHL" />

A traditional superstition that is prevalent among many of today's NHL players is that no player should either touch or hoist the Campbell or the [[Prince of Wales Trophy|Prince of Wales]] trophies when they have won the conference playoffs; the players feel that the [[Stanley Cup]] is the true championship trophy and thus it should be the only trophy that they should be hoisting.<ref>{{cite web | title=NHL.com - Ice Age: Having another trophy in mind | url=http://www.nhl.com/features/iceage/main060206.html | first=Phil | last=Coffey | date=2006-06-02|accessdate=2006-07-25}}</ref> Traditionally, the captain of the winning team poses with the trophy, and sometimes, the entire team poses as well.

